Preheat the oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{2} into 2cm wide wedges and pop on a #tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, @ground turmeric{1} and @nigella seeds{1/2%tsp}. Use your hands to rub the flavourings all over the wedges. Arrange in an even layer and roast in the middle of your oven until crisp and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, remove the @pistachios{25} from their shells and finely chop. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all). Trim and coarsely grate the @carrot{1}(coarsely grated). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Zest the @lemon{1/2}.

Pop the chickpeas into a large #bowl{}. Break them up with the back of a #fork{} then add the carrot, lemon zest, coriander, the @plain flour{24%g}, @Zanzibar Style Curry Powder{1} and @mango chutney{40%g}. Season with salt and pepper. Squish together with your hands until mushy and the mixture sticks together. Keep to one side.

Heat a splash of oil in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Fry the chickpea burgers in the hot oil until golden on both sides. This should take around ~{3-4%minutes} on each side.

Meanwhile, halve the @burger buns{2} and warm for ~{2%minutes} in the oven. Slice the @tomato{1%medium}. Pop the @wild rocket{20} in a bowl. Halve the @lemon{1/2} and add a squeeze of lemon juice to the rocket along with a splash of @olive oil{} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Toss together.

Spread a little @mayonnaise{2} over each bun half. Pop a chickpea burger on the bottom bun, then place some tomato slices on top. Top with a handful of rocket and sit the other half of the bun on top. Share the wedges between your plates and place the burger alongside. Serve with any remaining rocket and tomato on the side. Tuck in!

> Because of their texture, chickpeas make a great substitute for ground beef and work brilliantly alongside punchier flavours like our Zanzibar curry powder. Combined with chopped coriander, pistachios, grated carrot, and mango chutney, shaped into burger patties and fried until golden, they're the perfect thing to make for a midweek veggie treat.